<mods xmlns="http://www.loc.gov/mods/v3" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><identifier>81055/vdc_100024052050.0x000009_en</identifier><location><shelfLocator>IOR/R/15/1/149, ff 15-16</shelfLocator><url>http://www.qdl.qa/en/archive/81055/vdc_100024052050.0x000009</url><url access="preview">https://images.qdl.qa/iiif/images/81055/vdc_100000000193.0x00007a/IOR_R_15_1_149_0040.jp2/full/!1000,1000/0/default.jpg</url><physicalLocation>British Library: India Office Records and Private Papers</physicalLocation></location><recordInfo><recordIdentifer>IOR/R/15/1/149, ff 15-16</recordIdentifer></recordInfo><titleInfo><title>Letter no.544 of 1855 from Henry Anderson, Secretary to the Government of Bombay, to Captain Arnold Kemball, Resident in the Persian Gulf</title></titleInfo><originInfo><dateIssued>1855/1855</dateIssued><dateCaptured>2014-09-17T01:24:29</dateCaptured></originInfo><language><languageTerm authority="iso639-2b">eng</languageTerm></language><physicalDescription><extent>2 folios</extent></physicalDescription><abstract>The letter and its enclosure relate to the liberation in 1853 of thirty-six slaves by the Shaikh of Lingah [Bandar-e Lengeh]. Anderson writes that Kemball commend the Shaikh for his actions, on behalf of the Court of Directors. Enclosed with Anderson&#8217;s letter is an extract of paragraphs 7 and 8 of despatch no.32 of 1854 from the Court of Directors, dated 22 November 1854. Paragraph 7 gives credit to the Shaikh of Bandar-e Lengeh for his actions, noting that it is an indication of the disposition of the Persian authorities to act on their slave trade engagements. Paragraph 8 notes that the liberated slaves, most of whom were children, have been placed with Christian families or in the care of the Reverend Mr Candy at his institution in Chinchpoogly [Chinchpokli] in Bombay.</abstract><typeOfResource>text</typeOfResource><genre type="class">Letter</genre><accessCondition type="Use an